    detailedAnalysis: "## Market Overview\nThe Indian stock market has been witnessing a significant surge in foreign institutional investor (FII) inflows, with $2.5 billion invested in May alone. This has been driven by the attractiveness of Indian stocks, particularly in the IT and pharma sectors. According to data from the National Securities Depository Limited (NSDL), FIIs have invested $10.5 billion in Indian equities so far this year, with $6.2 billion coming in the last two months.\n## Key Developments\nThe FII inflows have been driven by the strong earnings growth of Indian companies, particularly in the IT and pharma sectors. The IT sector has seen a significant surge in FII inflows, with companies like Infosys and TCS witnessing strong buying. The pharma sector has also seen significant FII inflows, with companies like Sun Pharma and Dr. Reddy\'s witnessing strong buying.\n## Market Impact\nThe surge in FII inflows has had a significant impact on the Indian stock market, with the Sensex and Nifty rising to new highs. The Sensex has risen 4.5% in May, while the Nifty has risen 4.2%. The mid-cap and small-cap indices have also seen significant gains, with the BSE Mid-cap index rising 5.1% and the BSE Small-cap index rising 5.5%.\n## Expert Perspective\nAccording to analysts, the surge in FII inflows is a positive sign for the Indian stock market. \'The FII inflows are a vote of confidence in the Indian economy and the strong earnings growth of Indian companies,\' said Rohan Kapoor, an analyst at HDFC Securities. \'We expect the FII inflows to continue in the coming months, driven by the attractiveness of Indian stocks.\'\n## Historical Context\nThe Indian stock market has seen significant FII inflows in the past, particularly during the 2003-2007 bull run. However, the current surge in FII inflows is different, driven by the strong earnings growth of Indian companies and the attractiveness of Indian stocks.\n---\nAuthor: Shiva Sandeep\nTelegram: @its_terabyte\nPublished by PulseTrends",
